## 11. Implementation Standards

### File structure
- `lib/irregularity/jitter.ts` — `jitter()`, `pick()`, `asymmetricJitter()`, seeded PRNG.
- `lib/irregularity/humanEase.ts` — humanized easing curves (paired with `EASE` dictionary).
- `lib/irregularity/sceneAtmosphere.ts` — per-scene atmosphere derivation.
- `lib/irregularity/timing.ts` — `clusterDuration()`, pause beats, suspended moments.

### Hooks
- `useJitter(base, percent)` — memoized jitter for stable per-mount values.
- `useDelayedReaction(value, baseDelayMs)` — secondary reaction delay layer.
- `useChapterInstability(chapterId)` — picks one of (drift / pulse / flicker) at chapter mount.

### Seeding
- The PRNG seed is derived from `Date.now() & 0xffffffff` at app boot, stored in a context.
- Optionally accept a `?seed=` URL parameter for design review reproducibility.
- Per-chapter seeds derived as `seed XOR chapterIndex` so each chapter gets its own sub-stream.

### Reduced motion
Under `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce`:
- `jitter()` collapses to its base value (`percent → 0`).
- `pick()` always returns the first value of the array.
- Suspended moments are skipped.
- Sub-pixel cursor tremor is disabled.
- Atmospheric drift continues (it is not motion in the user's frame of reference).

### Performance
- All `jitter()` calls are O(1). PRNG is `mulberry32` (seedable, fast, zero-dependency).
- `jitter()` is **synchronous** and **inline** — no async, no batched scheduling.
- Atmosphere uniforms updated via `gsap.ticker` at 30 FPS (per `webgl-system.mdc`), not per-frame.

---

## 12. DO / DON'T

### DO
- DO route every variance through `jitter()` / `pick()` — never raw `Math.random()`.
- DO seed variance per session for internal consistency.
- DO bound variance to the locked envelope (Section 2).
- DO leave first/last cluster elements 15% longer than middle.
- DO let one element per scene "linger" or "skip a beat" deliberately.
- DO derive per-scene atmosphere from the chapter's declared atmosphere with bounded variance.
- DO insert dramatic pauses between scene reveals.
- DO reverse-engineer the variance budget from analog film references, not from intuition.

### DON'T
- DON'T use raw `Math.random()` in motion / atmosphere code.
- DON'T allow variance to break locked tokens — `jitter()` operates **inside** the envelope.
- DON'T add "glitch", "VHS", "lo-fi" effects — these are costume, not character.
- DON'T make hover-in and hover-out symmetrical durations.
- DON'T loop atmosphere shaders on perfect mathematical periods.
- DON'T disable irregularity in production — it **is** production.
- DON'T attempt to "balance out" variance to feel even — irregularity is the point.

---

## 13. Cinematic Rationale

- Locked tokens guarantee **coherence**. Bounded variance guarantees **life**. A system with only one is incomplete.
- The reason luxury cinematic web design eventually feels generic is that it lacks variance — every reveal is the same reveal, every transition is the same transition. The audience subconsciously detects the pattern within 30 seconds and disengages.
- Bounded, seeded variance creates **the impression of presence** — the user feels someone made this for them, not for everyone.
- The 15% emphasis on first/last cluster elements is a direct lift from musical phrasing (the held downbeat, the resolved final note) — applied to motion, it produces the same emotional weight.
- The ban on raw `Math.random()` is what separates this system from "hand-coded chaos". Variance must be **designed**, not **wild**.
